elements.content: Fourteen novel coordination compounds based on (4-carboxylphenyl) (4-(2′-carboxylphenyl)­benzyl) ether (H2L) and different N-donor ligands have been hydrothermally synthesized and structurally determined by single-crystal X-ray diffraction analyses, namely, [Zn3(L)3(biim-4)2]·H2O (1), [Cd­(L)­(H2O)­(biim-4)0.5] (2), [Zn­(L)­(BIE)] (3), [Co­(L)­(BIE)] (4), [Cd­(L)­(BIE)] (5), [Ni­(L)­(BIE)] (6), [Ni­(L)­(phen)]·H2O (7), [Co­(L)­(phen)]·H2O (8), [Co­(HL)2(phen)2]·3H2O (9), [Cd­(L)­(H2O)­(phen)] (10), [Co­(L)­(H2O)­(phen)] (11), [Cd­(L)­(phen)2] (12), [Pb­(L)] (13), and [Pb­(L)­(phen)]·H2O (14), where biim-4 = 1,1′-(1,4-butanediyl)­bis­(imidazole), BIE = 2,2′-bis­(1H-imidazolyl)­ether, and phen = 1,10-phenanthroline. Compound 1 displays an unusual three-dimensional (3D) binodal (4,5)-connected net with a point symbol of (43·62·8)­(45·5·64). Compound 2 exhibits one-dimensional (1D) looplike chain structures, which are further extended into a 3D supramolecular architecture through π–π interactions. Compounds 3–6 are isomorphous and feature similar two-dimensional (2D) layer structures. Compounds 7 and 8 are isomorphous and show the same zero-dimensional (0D) structures, which are further extended by π–π interactions into 2D supramolecular layers. Compound 9 displays a discrete [Co2(L)2(phen)2] dimer. Neighboring dimers are further linked by π–π interactions to form a 1D double chain. Compounds 10 and 11 exhibit similar 1D double chain structures. The chains are further linked via π–π interactions to generate 2D supramolecular layers. Compound 12 shows a discrete [Cd2(L)2(phen)2] dimer. The π–π stacking and hydrogen-bonding interactions further extend the dimers into a 3D supramolecular architecture. Compound 13 displays a typical (44)-sql network structure. Neighboring networks are further linked by the π–π interactions, leading to an unusual 3D supramolecular architecture. Compound 14 exhibits a discrete [Pb2(L)2(phen)2] dimer. Neighboring dimers are further linked by the π–π interactions to form a 2D supramolecular layer. The thermal stabilities and luminescent properties of the complexes have also been investigated in detail.

A series of complexes based on H2L and various N-donor ligands have been successfully prepared under hydrothermal conditions, and their photoluminescent properties have also been investigated.

Introduction

The keen interest in the design and synthesis of coordination complexes stems not only from their fascinating variety of unusual topologies and architectures but also from their tremendous potential applications in functional materials. Generally, the construction of coordination compounds depends on the combination of several factors, such as coordination geometry of central metal and neutral N-donor ligands, the nature of anions, reaction conditions, and so on. The nature of anions plays a great role in determining the network structure of a compound. In this regard, the coordination complexes based on rigid polycarboxylic acids providing reliable coordination modes, such as benzene-tricarboxylic acid and benzene-tetracarboxylic acid, have been widely studied. However, relatively less attention has been given to supramolecular architectures based on the flexible polycarboxylic acids, especially flexible aromatic dicarboxylates. Among these, the flexible (4-carboxylphenyl) (4-(2′-carboxylphenyl)­benzyl) ether (H2L) may be a good candidate for the construction of coordination complexes with new topologies and useful properties. In the H2L molecule, the aromatic rings can freely bend and rotate to meet the coordination geometries of the central metal cations because of the presence of the flexible −O–CH2– spacer. In addition, the H2L ligand can easily form π–π interactions due to the existence of a conjugated biphenyl system.

Experimental Section

Materials and Measurements

All reagents and solvents for syntheses were purchased from commercial sources and used as received. The ligands biim-4 and BIE were synthesized according to the literature. The C, H, and N elemental analysis was conducted on a Perkin-Elmer 240C elemental analyzer. X-ray powder diffraction patterns (XRPD) were performed on a Siemens D5005 diffractometer. The Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) spectra were recorded from KBr pellets in the range 4000-400 cm-1 on a Mattson Alpha-Centauri spectrometer. The photoluminescent properties were measured on a Perkin-Elmer FLS-920 spectrometer. TGA was performed on a Perkin-Elmer TG-7 analyzer heated from 40 to 600 °C under nitrogen gas.

X-ray Crystallography

Crystallographic diffraction data for compounds 1-14 were collected on a Oxford Diffraction Gemini R CCD with graphite-monochromated Mo-Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å) at 293 K. Absorption corrections were applied using multiscan technique. All the structures were solved by the direct method of SHELXS-97 and refined by full-matrix least-squares techniques using the SHELXL-97 program within WINGX. Non-hydrogen atoms were refined with anisotropic temperature parameters. The hydrogen atoms attached to carbons, and the hydrogen atoms of hydroxyl in compound 9 were generated geometrically. Some water H atoms in compounds 1, 9, and 14 were not located from a difference Fourier map.

Effects of the Central Metal Cations on the Frameworks

It should be noted that the central metal cations also have a significant function on the complex structures. The different coordination environments of the central metals result in different structures of 1 and 2, as well as 7, 9, 10, and 14. For compounds 1 and 2, the coordination numbers of Zn­(II) cations in 1 are lower than those of Cd­(II) cations in 2. In 1, Zn­(II) cations adopt slightly distorted tetrahedral and tetragonal pyramid coordination geometries, respectively. The L anions and biim-4 ligands bridge the Zn­(II) cations to generate a complicated 3D framework. In 2, the six-coordinated Cd­(II) cations are bridged by the biim-4 ligands to furnish a 1D looplike chain. For compounds 7, 9, 10, and 14, the central metal cations are six-coordinated, but their coordination environments are different. For example, in 7, each Ni­(II) cation is surrounded by two nitrogen atoms from one phen ligand and four carboxylate oxygen atoms from two L anions. Two Ni­(II) cations are bridged by two L anions to form a dimeric unit. However, each six-coordinated Cd­(II) cation in 10 is surrounded by two nitrogen atoms from one phen ligand and four oxygen atoms from three L anions and one water molecule. The Cd­(II) cations are bridged by L anions to generate a 1D double chain. Clearly, the structural difference between these compounds may be attributed to the difference in the coordination environments of the central metals.

Conclusions

Fourteen complexes based on (4-carboxylphenyl) (4-(2'-carboxylphenyl)benzyl) ether and structurally related N-donor ligands have been hydrothermally synthesized. The compounds 1-14 show intriguing 0D, 1D, 2D, and 3D structures. The structural diversities of the complexes not only demonstrate that the H2L is a good candidate for the construction of coordination compounds with aesthetic structures but also indicate that the N-donor ligands and the central metals play great roles in the formation of the complexes. Additionally, the π-π stacking interactions and hydrogen-bonding interactions contributed the formation of the supramolecular architectures. The luminescent properties indicate that compounds 1-3, 5, 10, and 12 may be good candidates for optical materials.
